# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: electrochemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] When a chemical reaction is driven by an electrical potential difference, as in electrolysis, or if a potential difference results from a chemical reaction as in an electric battery or fuel cell, it is called an *electrochemical* reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In electrochemical reactions, unlike in other chemical reactions, electrons are not transferred directly between atoms, ions, or molecules, but via the aforementioned electric circuit.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This phenomenon is what distinguishes an electrochemical reaction from a conventional chemical reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Understanding of electrical matters began in the sixteenth century.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] During this century, the English scientist William Gilbert spent 17 years experimenting with magnetism and, to a lesser extent, electricity.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] For his work on magnets, Gilbert became known as the *"Father of Magnetism."* He discovered various methods for producing and strengthening magnets.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1663, the German physicist Otto von Guericke created the first electric generator, which produced static electricity by applying friction in the machine.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The generator was made of a large sulfur ball cast inside a glass globe, mounted on a shaft.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The ball was rotated by means of a crank and an electric spark was produced when a pad was rubbed against the ball as it rotated.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The globe could be removed and used as source for experiments with electricity.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] By the mid-18th century the French chemist Charles François de Cisternay du Fay had discovered two types of static electricity, and that like charges repel each other whilst unlike charges attract.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Du Fay announced that electricity consisted of two fluids: *"vitreous"* (from the Latin for *"glass"*), or positive, electricity; and *"resinous,"* or negative, electricity.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This was the *two-fluid theory* of electricity, which was to be opposed by Benjamin Franklin's *one-fluid theory* later in the century.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1785, Charles-Augustin de Coulomb developed the law of electrostatic attraction as an outgrowth of his attempt to investigate the law of electrical repulsions as stated by Joseph Priestley in England.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In his essay Galvani concluded that animal tissue contained a here-to-fore neglected innate, vital force, which he termed *"animal electricity,"* which activated nerves and muscles spanned by metal probes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] He believed that this new force was a form of electricity in addition to the *"natural"* form produced by lightning or by the electric eel and torpedo ray as well as the *"artificial"* form produced by friction (i.e., static electricity).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Galvani's scientific colleagues generally accepted his views, but Alessandro Volta rejected the idea of an *"animal electric fluid,"* replying that the frog's legs responded to differences in metal temper, composition, and bulk.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Galvani refuted this by obtaining muscular action with two pieces of the same material.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Nevertheless, Volta's experimentation led him to develop the first practical battery, which took advantage of the relatively high energy (weak bonding) of zinc and could deliver an electrical current for much longer than any other device known at the time.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1800, William Nicholson and Johann Wilhelm Ritter succeeded in decomposing water into hydrogen and oxygen by electrolysis using Volta's battery.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Soon thereafter Ritter discovered the process of electroplating.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] He also observed that the amount of metal deposited and the amount of oxygen produced during an electrolytic process depended on the distance between the electrodes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] By 1801, Ritter observed thermoelectric currents and anticipated the discovery of thermoelectricity by Thomas Johann Seebeck.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] By the 1810s, William Hyde Wollaston made improvements to the galvanic cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Sir Humphry Davy's work with electrolysis led to the conclusion that the production of electricity in simple electrolytic cells resulted from chemical action and that chemical combination occurred between substances of opposite charge.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This work led directly to the isolation of metallic sodium and potassium by electrolysis of their molten salts, and of the alkaline earth metals from theirs, in 1808.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Hans Christian Ørsted's discovery of the magnetic effect of electric currents in 1820 was immediately recognized as an epoch-making advance, although he left further work on electromagnetism to others.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] André-Marie Ampère quickly repeated Ørsted's experiment, and formulated them mathematically.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1821, Estonian-German physicist Thomas Johann Seebeck demonstrated the electrical potential between the juncture points of two dissimilar metals when there is a temperature difference between the joints.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1827, the German scientist Georg Ohm expressed his law in this famous book *"Die galvanische Kette, mathematisch bearbeitet"* (The Galvanic Circuit Investigated Mathematically) in which he gave his complete theory of electricity.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1832, Michael Faraday's experiments led him to state his two laws of electrochemistry.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1836, John Daniell invented a primary cell which solved the problem of polarization by introducing copper ions into the solution near the positive electrode and thus eliminating hydrogen gas generation.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Later results revealed that at the other electrode, amalgamated zinc (i.e., zinc alloyed with mercury) would produce a higher voltage.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] William Grove produced the first fuel cell in 1839.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1846, Wilhelm Weber developed the electrodynamometer.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1868, Georges Leclanché patented a new cell which eventually became the forerunner to the world's first widely used battery, the zinc–carbon cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Svante Arrhenius published his thesis in 1884 on *Recherches sur la conductibilité galvanique des électrolytes* (Investigations on the galvanic conductivity of electrolytes).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] From his results the author concluded that electrolytes, when dissolved in water, become to varying degrees split or dissociated into electrically opposite positive and negative ions.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Hall developed an efficient method (the Hall–Héroult process) to obtain aluminium using electrolysis of molten alumina.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1894, Friedrich Ostwald concluded important studies of the conductivity and electrolytic dissociation of organic acids.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Walther Hermann Nernst developed the theory of the electromotive force of the voltaic cell in 1888.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1889, he showed how the characteristics of the voltage produced could be used to calculate the free energy change in the chemical reaction producing the voltage.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] He constructed an equation, known as Nernst equation, which related the voltage of a cell to its properties.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1898, Fritz Haber showed that definite reduction products can result from electrolytic processes if the potential at the cathode is kept constant.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1898, he explained the reduction of nitrobenzene in stages at the cathode and this became the model for other similar reduction processes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1902, The Electrochemical Society (ECS) was founded.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1909, Robert Andrews Millikan began a series of experiments (see oil drop experiment) to determine the electric charge carried by a single electron.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1911, Harvey Fletcher, working with Millikan, was successful in measuring the charge on the electron, by replacing the water droplets used by Millikan, which quickly evaporated, with oil droplets.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Within one day Fletcher measured the charge of an electron within several decimal places.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1923, Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Martin Lowry published essentially the same theory about how acids and bases behave, using an electrochemical basis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In 1937, Arne Tiselius developed the first sophisticated electrophoretic apparatus.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Some years later, he was awarded the 1948 Nobel Prize for his work in protein electrophoresis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A year later, in 1949, the International Society of Electrochemistry (ISE) was founded.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] By the 1960s–1970s quantum electrochemistry was developed by Revaz Dogonadze and his students.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The term "redox" stands for **reduction-oxidation**.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] It refers to electrochemical processes involving electron transfer to or from a molecule or ion, changing its oxidation state.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This reaction can occur through the application of an external voltage or through the release of chemical energy.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Oxidation and reduction describe the change of oxidation state that takes place in the atoms, ions or molecules involved in an electrochemical reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Formally, oxidation state is the hypothetical charge that an atom would have if all bonds to atoms of different elements were 100% ionic.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] An atom or ion that gives up an electron to another atom or ion has its oxidation state increase, and the recipient of the negatively charged electron has its oxidation state decrease.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] For example, when atomic sodium reacts with atomic chlorine, sodium donates one electron and attains an oxidation state of +1.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Chlorine accepts the electron and its oxidation state is reduced to −1.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The sign of the oxidation state (positive/negative) actually corresponds to the value of each ion's electronic charge.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The attraction of the differently charged sodium and chlorine ions is the reason they then form an ionic bond.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The loss of electrons from an atom or molecule is called oxidation, and the gain of electrons is reduction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This can be easily remembered through the use of mnemonic devices.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Two of the most popular are *"OIL RIG"* (Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain) and *"LEO"* the lion says *"GER"* (Lose Electrons: Oxidation, Gain Electrons: Reduction).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Oxidation and reduction always occur in a paired fashion such that one species is oxidized when another is reduced.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] For cases where electrons are shared (covalent bonds) between atoms with large differences in electronegativity, the electron is assigned to the atom with the largest electronegativity in determining the oxidation state.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The atom or molecule which loses electrons is known as the *reducing agent*, or *reductant*, and the substance which accepts the electrons is called the *oxidizing agent*, or *oxidant*.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Thus, the oxidizing agent is always being reduced in a reaction; the reducing agent is always being oxidized.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Oxygen is a common oxidizing agent, but not the only one.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Despite the name, an oxidation reaction does not necessarily need to involve oxygen.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In fact, a fire can be fed by an oxidant other than oxygen; fluorine fires are often unquenchable, as fluorine is an even stronger oxidant (it has a weaker bond and higher electronegativity, and thus accepts electrons even better) than oxygen.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] For reactions involving oxygen, the gain of oxygen implies the oxidation of the atom or molecule to which the oxygen is added (and the oxygen is reduced).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In organic compounds, such as butane or ethanol, the loss of hydrogen implies oxidation of the molecule from which it is lost (and the hydrogen is reduced).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This follows because the hydrogen donates its electron in covalent bonds with non-metals but it takes the electron along when it is lost.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Conversely, loss of oxygen or gain of hydrogen implies reduction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Electrochemical reactions in water are better analyzed by using the ion-electron method, where H+, OH− ion, H2O and electrons (to compensate the oxidation changes) are added to the cell's half-reactions for oxidation and reduction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In acidic medium, H+ ions and water are added to balance each half-reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] For example, when manganese reacts with sodium bismuthate.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In basic medium, OH− ions and water are added to balance each half-reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Here, 'spectator ions' (K+, Na+) were omitted from the half-reactions.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] An electrochemical cell is a device that produces an electric current from energy released by a spontaneous redox reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This kind of cell includes the Galvanic cell or Voltaic cell, named after Luigi Galvani and Alessandro Volta, both scientists who conducted experiments on chemical reactions and electric current during the late 18th century.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Electrochemical cells have two conductive electrodes (the anode and the cathode).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The anode is defined as the electrode where oxidation occurs and the cathode is the electrode where the reduction takes place.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Electrodes can be made from any sufficiently conductive materials, such as metals, semiconductors, graphite, and even conductive polymers.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In between these electrodes is the electrolyte, which contains ions that can freely move.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The galvanic cell uses two different metal electrodes, each in an electrolyte where the positively charged ions are the oxidized form of the electrode metal.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] One electrode will undergo oxidation (the anode) and the other will undergo reduction (the cathode).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The metal of the anode will oxidize, going from an oxidation state of 0 (in the solid form) to a positive oxidation state and become an ion.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] At the cathode, the metal ion in solution will accept one or more electrons from the cathode and the ion's oxidation state is reduced to 0.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This forms a solid metal that electrodeposits on the cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The two electrodes must be electrically connected to each other, allowing for a flow of electrons that leave the metal of the anode and flow through this connection to the ions at the surface of the cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This flow of electrons is an electric current that can be used to do work, such as turn a motor or power a light.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A galvanic cell whose electrodes are zinc and copper submerged in zinc sulfate and copper sulfate, respectively, is known as a Daniell cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In this example, the anode is the zinc metal which is oxidized (loses electrons) to form zinc ions in solution, and copper ions accept electrons from the copper metal electrode and the ions deposit at the copper cathode as an electrodeposit.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This cell forms a simple battery as it will spontaneously generate a flow of electric current from the anode to the cathode through the external connection.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This reaction can be driven in reverse by applying a voltage, resulting in the deposition of zinc metal at the anode and formation of copper ions at the cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] To provide a complete electric circuit, there must also be an ionic conduction path between the anode and cathode electrolytes in addition to the electron conduction path.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The simplest ionic conduction path is to provide a liquid junction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] To avoid mixing between the two electrolytes, the liquid junction can be provided through a porous plug that allows ion flow while minimizing electrolyte mixing.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] To further minimize mixing of the electrolytes, a salt bridge can be used which consists of an electrolyte saturated gel in an inverted U-tube.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] As the negatively charged electrons flow in one direction around this circuit, the positively charged metal ions flow in the opposite direction in the electrolyte.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A voltmeter is capable of measuring the change of electrical potential between the anode and the cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The electrochemical cell voltage is also referred to as electromotive force or emf.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A cell diagram can be used to trace the path of the electrons in the electrochemical cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] First, the reduced form of the metal to be oxidized at the anode (Zn) is written.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This is separated from its oxidized form by a vertical line, which represents the limit between the phases (oxidation changes).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The double vertical lines represent the saline bridge on the cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Finally, the oxidized form of the metal to be reduced at the cathode, is written, separated from its reduced form by the vertical line.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The electrolyte concentration is given as it is an important variable in determining the exact cell potential.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] To allow prediction of the cell potential, tabulations of standard electrode potential are available.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Such tabulations are referenced to the standard hydrogen electrode (SHE).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] which is shown as a reduction but, in fact, the SHE can act as either the anode or the cathode, depending on the relative oxidation/reduction potential of the other electrode/electrolyte combination.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The term standard in SHE requires a supply of hydrogen gas bubbled through the electrolyte at a pressure of 1 atm and an acidic electrolyte with H+ activity equal to 1 (usually assumed to be [H+] = 1 mol/liter, i.e. pH = 0).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The SHE electrode can be connected to any other electrode by a salt bridge and an external circuit to form a cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] If the second electrode is also at standard conditions, then the measured cell potential is called the standard electrode potential for the electrode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The standard electrode potential for the SHE is zero, by definition.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The polarity of the standard electrode potential provides information about the relative reduction potential of the electrode compared to the SHE.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] If the electrode has a positive potential with respect to the SHE, then that means it is a strongly reducing electrode which forces the SHE to be the anode (an example is Cu in aqueous CuSO4 with a standard electrode potential of 0.337 V).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Conversely, if the measured potential is negative, the electrode is more oxidizing than the SHE (such as Zn in ZnSO4 where the standard electrode potential is −0.76 V).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Standard electrode potentials are usually tabulated as reduction potentials.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] However, the reactions are reversible and the role of a particular electrode in a cell depends on the relative oxidation/reduction potential of both electrodes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The oxidation potential for a particular electrode is just the negative of the reduction potential.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A standard cell potential can be determined by looking up the standard electrode potentials for both electrodes (sometimes called half cell potentials).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The one that is smaller will be the anode and will undergo oxidation.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The cell potential is then calculated as the sum of the reduction potential for the cathode and the oxidation potential for the anode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] At standard temperature, pressure and concentration conditions, the cell's emf (measured by a multimeter) is 0.34 V.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] By definition, the electrode potential for the SHE is zero.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Changes in the stoichiometric coefficients of a balanced cell equation will not change the *E*°red value because the standard electrode potential is an intensive property.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] During operation of an electrochemical cell, chemical energy is transformed into electrical energy.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This can be expressed mathematically as the product of the cell's emf *E*cell measured in volts (V) and the electric charge $Q_{e,trans}$ transferred through the external circuit.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] $Q_{\mathrm {e,trans} }$ is the cell current integrated over time and measured in coulombs (C); it can also be determined by multiplying the total number *n*e of electrons transferred (measured in moles) times Faraday's constant (*F*).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The emf of the cell at zero current is the maximum possible emf.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] It can be used to calculate the maximum possible electrical energy that could be obtained from a chemical reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] where work is defined as positive when it increases the energy of the system.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A positive cell potential gives a negative change in Gibbs free energy.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This is consistent with the cell production of an electric current from the cathode to the anode through the external circuit.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] If the current is driven in the opposite direction by imposing an external potential, then work is done on the cell to drive electrolysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A spontaneous electrochemical reaction (change in Gibbs free energy less than zero) can be used to generate an electric current in electrochemical cells.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This is the basis of all batteries and fuel cells.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] For example, gaseous oxygen (O2) and hydrogen (H2) can be combined in a fuel cell to form water and energy, typically a combination of heat and electrical energy.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Conversely, non-spontaneous electrochemical reactions can be driven forward by the application of a current at sufficient voltage.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The electrolysis of water into gaseous oxygen and hydrogen is a typical example.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The standard potential of an electrochemical cell requires standard conditions (Δ*G*°) for all of the reactants.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] When reactant concentrations differ from standard conditions, the cell potential will deviate from the standard potential.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In the 20th century German chemist Walther Nernst proposed a mathematical model to determine the effect of reactant concentration on electrochemical cell potential.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Gibbs' key contribution was to formalize the understanding of the effect of reactant concentration on spontaneity.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Based on Gibbs' work, Nernst extended the theory to include the contribution from electric potential on charged species.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] As shown in the previous section, the change in Gibbs free energy for an electrochemical cell can be related to the cell potential.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Here *ne* is the number of electrons (in moles), *F* is the Faraday constant (in coulombs/mole), and Δ*E* is the cell potential (in volts).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Note that *⁠RT/F⁠* is also known as the thermal voltage *V*T and is found in the study of plasmas and semiconductors as well.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The value 0.05916 V in the above equation is just the thermal voltage at standard temperature multiplied by the natural logarithm of 10.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A concentration cell is an electrochemical cell where the two electrodes are the same material, the electrolytes on the two half-cells involve the same ions, but the electrolyte concentration differs between the two half-cells.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] An example is an electrochemical cell, where two copper electrodes are submerged in two copper(II) sulfate solutions, whose concentrations are 0.05 M and 2.0 M, connected through a salt bridge.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This type of cell will generate a potential that can be predicted by the Nernst equation.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Le Chatelier's principle indicates that the reaction is more favorable to reduction as the concentration of Cu2+ ions increases.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Reduction will take place in the cell's compartment where the concentration is higher and oxidation will occur on the more dilute side.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The value of *E*° in this kind of cell is zero, as electrodes and ions are the same in both half-cells.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] However, this value is only approximate, as reaction quotient is defined in terms of ion activities which can be approximated with the concentrations as calculated here.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The Nernst equation plays an important role in understanding electrical effects in cells and organelles.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Such effects include nerve synapses and cardiac beat as well as the resting potential of a somatic cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Many types of battery have been commercialized and represent an important practical application of electrochemistry.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Early wet cells powered the first telegraph and telephone systems, and were the source of current for electroplating.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The zinc-manganese dioxide dry cell was the first portable, non-spillable battery type that made flashlights and other portable devices practical.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The mercury battery using zinc and mercuric oxide provided higher levels of power and capacity than the original dry cell for early electronic devices, but has been phased out of common use due to the danger of mercury pollution from discarded cells.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The lead–acid battery was the first practical secondary (rechargeable) battery that could have its capacity replenished from an external source.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The electrochemical reaction that produced current was (to a useful degree) reversible, allowing electrical energy and chemical energy to be interchanged as needed.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Common lead acid batteries contain a mixture of sulfuric acid and water, as well as lead plates.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The most common mixture used today is 30% acid.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] One problem, however, is if left uncharged acid will crystallize within the lead plates of the battery rendering it useless.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] These batteries last an average of 3 years with daily use but it is not unheard of for a lead acid battery to still be functional after 7–10 years.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Lead-acid cells continue to be widely used in automobiles.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] All the preceding types have water-based electrolytes, which limits the maximum voltage per cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The freezing of water limits low temperature performance.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The lithium metal battery, which does not (and cannot) use water in the electrolyte, provides improved performance over other types; a rechargeable lithium-ion battery is an essential part of many mobile devices.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The flow battery, an experimental type, offers the option of vastly larger energy capacity because its reactants can be replenished from external reservoirs.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The fuel cell can turn the chemical energy bound in hydrocarbon gases or hydrogen and oxygen directly into electrical energy with a much higher efficiency than any combustion process; such devices have powered many spacecraft and are being applied to grid energy storage for the public power system.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Corrosion is an electrochemical process, which reveals itself as rust or tarnish on metals like iron or copper and their respective alloys, steel and brass.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] For iron rust to occur the metal has to be in contact with oxygen and water.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The chemical reactions for this process are relatively complex and not all of them are completely understood.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] One area on the surface of the metal acts as the anode, which is where the oxidation (corrosion) occurs.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] At the anode, the metal gives up electrons.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] on the cathode, which is placed in another region of the metal.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Iron corrosion takes place in an acid medium; H+ ions come from reaction between carbon dioxide in the atmosphere and water, forming carbonic acid.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Iron(III) oxide hydrate is known as rust.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The concentration of water associated with iron oxide varies, thus the chemical formula is represented by Fe2O3·xH2O.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] An electric circuit is formed as passage of electrons and ions occurs; thus if an electrolyte is present it will facilitate oxidation, explaining why rusting is quicker in salt water.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Coinage metals, such as copper and silver, slowly corrode through use.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A patina of green-blue copper carbonate forms on the surface of copper with exposure to the water and carbon dioxide in the air.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Silver coins or cutlery that are exposed to high sulfur foods such as eggs or the low levels of sulfur species in the air develop a layer of black silver sulfide.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Gold and platinum are extremely difficult to oxidize under normal circumstances, and require exposure to a powerful chemical oxidizing agent such as aqua regia.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Some common metals oxidize extremely rapidly in air.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Titanium and aluminium oxidize instantaneously in contact with the oxygen in the air.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] These metals form an extremely thin layer of oxidized metal on the surface, which bonds with the underlying metal.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This thin oxide layer protects the underlying bulk of the metal from the air preventing the entire metal from oxidizing.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] These metals are used in applications where corrosion resistance is important.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Iron, in contrast, has an oxide that forms in air and water, called rust, that does not bond with the iron and therefore does not stop the further oxidation of the iron.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Thus iron left exposed to air and water will continue to rust until all of the iron is oxidized.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Attempts to save a metal from becoming anodic are of two general types.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Anodic regions dissolve and destroy the structural integrity of the metal.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] While it is almost impossible to prevent anode/cathode formation, if a non-conducting material covers the metal, contact with the electrolyte is not possible and corrosion will not occur.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Metals can be coated with paint or other less conductive metals (*passivation*).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This prevents the metal surface from being exposed to electrolytes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Scratches exposing the metal substrate will result in corrosion.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The region under the coating adjacent to the scratch acts as the anode of the reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] A method commonly used to protect a structural metal is to attach a metal which is more anodic than the metal to be protected.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This forces the structural metal to be cathodic, thus spared corrosion.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] It is called *"sacrificial"* because the anode dissolves and has to be replaced periodically.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Zinc bars are attached to various locations on steel ship hulls to render the ship hull cathodic.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The zinc bars are replaced periodically.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Other metals, such as magnesium, would work very well but zinc is the least expensive useful metal.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] To protect pipelines, an ingot of buried or exposed magnesium (or zinc) is buried beside the pipeline and is connected electrically to the pipe above ground.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The pipeline is forced to be a cathode and is protected from being oxidized and rusting.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] At intervals new ingots are buried to replace those dissolved.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The spontaneous redox reactions of a conventional battery produce electricity through the different reduction potentials of the cathode and anode in the electrolyte.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] However, electrolysis requires an external source of electrical energy to induce a chemical reaction, and this process takes place in a compartment called an electrolytic cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] When molten, the salt sodium chloride can be electrolyzed to yield metallic sodium and gaseous chlorine.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Industrially this process takes place in a special cell named Downs cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The cell is connected to an electrical power supply, allowing electrons to migrate from the power supply to the electrolytic cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This process can yield large amounts of metallic sodium and gaseous chlorine, and is widely used in mineral dressing and metallurgy industries.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The emf for this process is approximately −4 V indicating a (very) non-spontaneous process.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In order for this reaction to occur the power supply should provide at least a potential difference of 4 V.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] However, larger voltages must be used for this reaction to occur at a high rate.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Water can be converted to its component elemental gases, H2 and O2, through the application of an external voltage.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Water does not decompose into hydrogen and oxygen spontaneously as the Gibbs free energy change for the process at standard conditions is very positive, about 474.4 kJ.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The decomposition of water into hydrogen and oxygen can be performed in an electrolytic cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In it, a pair of inert electrodes usually made of platinum immersed in water act as anode and cathode in the electrolytic process.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The electrolysis starts with the application of an external voltage between the electrodes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This process will not occur except at extremely high voltages without an electrolyte such as sodium chloride or sulfuric acid (most used 0.1 M).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Bubbles from the gases will be seen near both electrodes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Although strong acids may be used in the apparatus, the reaction will not net consume the acid.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] While this reaction will work at any conductive electrode at a sufficiently large potential, platinum catalyzes both hydrogen and oxygen formation, allowing for relatively low voltages (~2 V depending on the pH).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Electrolysis in an aqueous solution is a similar process as mentioned in electrolysis of water.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] However, it is considered to be a complex process because the contents in solution have to be analyzed in half reactions, whether reduced or oxidized.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The presence of water in a solution of sodium chloride must be examined in respect to its reduction and oxidation in both electrodes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Usually, water is electrolysed as mentioned above in electrolysis of water yielding *gaseous oxygen in the anode* and gaseous hydrogen in the cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] On the other hand, sodium chloride in water dissociates in Na+ and Cl− ions.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The cation, which is the positive ion, will be attracted to the cathode (−), thus reducing the sodium ion.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The chloride anion will then be attracted to the anode (+), where it is oxidized to chlorine gas.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Reaction 1 is discarded as it has the most negative value on standard reduction potential thus making it less thermodynamically favorable in the process.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] When comparing the reduction potentials in reactions 2 and 4, the oxidation of chloride ion is favored over oxidation of water, thus chlorine gas is produced at the anode and not oxygen gas.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Although the initial analysis is correct, there is another effect, known as the overvoltage effect.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Additional voltage is sometimes required, beyond the voltage predicted by the *E*°cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] This may be due to kinetic rather than thermodynamic considerations.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In fact, it has been proven that the activation energy for the chloride ion is very low, hence favorable in kinetic terms.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In other words, although the voltage applied is thermodynamically sufficient to drive electrolysis, the rate is so slow that to make the process proceed in a reasonable time frame, the voltage of the external source has to be increased (hence, overvoltage).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] As the overall reaction indicates, the concentration of chloride ions is reduced in comparison to OH− ions (whose concentration increases).
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The reaction also shows the production of gaseous hydrogen, chlorine and aqueous sodium hydroxide.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Quantitative aspects of electrolysis were originally developed by Michael Faraday in 1834.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Faraday is also credited to have coined the terms *electrolyte*, electrolysis, among many others while he studied quantitative analysis of electrochemical reactions.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Also he was an advocate of the law of conservation of energy.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Faraday concluded after several experiments on electric current in a non-spontaneous process that the mass of the products yielded on the electrodes was proportional to the value of current supplied to the cell, the length of time the current existed, and the molar mass of the substance analyzed.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In other words, the amount of a substance deposited on each electrode of an electrolytic cell is directly proportional to the quantity of electricity passed through the cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Faraday devised the laws of chemical electrodeposition of metals from solutions in 1857.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] An important aspect of the second law of electrolysis is electroplating, which together with the first law of electrolysis has a significant number of applications in industry, as when used to protectively coat metals to avoid corrosion.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] The generation of chemical energy through photosynthesis is inherently an electrochemical process, as is production of metals like aluminum and titanium from their ores.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Certain diabetes blood sugar meters measure the amount of glucose in the blood through its redox potential.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] In addition to established electrochemical technologies (like deep cycle lead acid batteries) there is also a wide range of new emerging technologies such as fuel cells, large format lithium-ion batteries, electrochemical reactors and super-capacitors that are becoming increasingly commercial.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Electrochemical or coulometric titrations were introduced for quantitative analysis of minute quantities in 1938 by the Hungarian chemists László Szebellédy and Zoltan Somogyi.
[src:electrochemistry/electrochemistry] Electrochemistry also has important applications in the food industry, like the assessment of food/package interactions, the analysis of milk composition, the characterization and the determination of the freezing end-point of ice-cream mixes, or the determination of free acidity in olive oil.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] In electrochemistry, **electrode potential** is the voltage of a galvanic cell built from a standard reference electrode and another electrode to be characterized.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] The standard electrode potential is a conventional instance of this concept whose reference electrode is the standard hydrogen electrode (SHE), defined to have a potential of zero volts.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] It may also be defined as the potential difference between the charged metallic rods and salt solution.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] The electrode potential has its origin in the potential difference developed at the interface between the electrode and the electrolyte.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] It is common, for instance, to speak of the electrode potential of the M+/M redox couple.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] Electrode potential appears at the interface between an electrode and electrolyte due to the transfer of charged species across the interface, specific adsorption of ions at the interface, and specific adsorption/orientation of polar molecules, including those of the solvent.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] Reversible potentials can be sometimes converted to the standard electrode potential for a given electroactive species by extrapolation of the measured values to the standard state.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] The value of the electrode potential under non-equilibrium depends on the nature and composition of the contacting phases, and on the kinetics of electrode reactions at the interface (see Butler–Volmer equation).
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] 3. reference electrode (standard hydrogen electrode or an equivalent).
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] The potential measurements are performed with the positive terminal of the electrometer connected to the working electrode and the negative terminal to the reference electrode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] 2. convention "Gibbs–Ostwald–Stockholm" (sometimes referred to as "European").
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] In 1953 in Stockholm IUPAC recognized that either of the conventions is permissible; however, it unanimously recommended that only the magnitude expressed according to the convention (2) be called "the electrode potential".
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] To avoid possible ambiguities, the electrode potential thus defined can also be referred to as *Gibbs–Stockholm electrode potential*.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] In both conventions, the standard hydrogen electrode is defined to have a potential of 0 V.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] Both conventions also agree on the sign of E for a half-cell reaction when it is written as a reduction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] The main difference between the two conventions is that upon reversing the direction of a half-cell reaction *as written*, according to the convention (1) the sign of E also switches, whereas in the convention (2) it does not.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] The logic behind switching the sign of E is to maintain the correct sign relationship with the Gibbs free energy change, given by Δ*G* = −*nFE* where n is the number of electrons involved and F is the Faraday constant.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] It is assumed that the half-reaction is balanced by the appropriate SHE half-reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] Since Δ*G* switches sign when a reaction is written in reverse, so too, proponents of the convention (1) argue, should the sign of E.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] Proponents of the convention (2) argue that all reported electrode potentials should be consistent with the electrostatic sign of the relative potential difference.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] This follows from the IUPAC definition of the electric potential difference of a galvanic cell, according to which the electric potential difference of a cell is the difference of the potentials of the electrodes on the right and the left of the galvanic cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrode-potential] When Δ*V*cell is positive, then positive electrical charge flows through the cell from the left electrode (anode) to the right electrode (cathode).
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In chemistry and manufacturing, **electrolysis** is a technique that uses direct electric current (DC) to drive an otherwise non-spontaneous biological and physical reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Electrolysis is commercially important as a stage in the separation of elements from naturally occurring sources such as ores using an electrolytic cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The voltage that is needed for electrolysis to occur is called the decomposition potential.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The word "electrolysis" was introduced by Michael Faraday in 1834, using the Greek words ἤλεκτρον [ɛ̌ːlektron] "amber", which since the 17th century was associated with electrical phenomena, and *λύσις* [lýsis] meaning "dissolution".
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Nevertheless, electrolysis, as a tool to study chemical reactions and obtain pure elements, precedes the coinage of the term and formal description by Faraday.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In the early nineteenth century, William Nicholson and Anthony Carlisle sought to further Volta's experiments.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] They attached two wires to either side of a voltaic pile and placed the other ends in a tube filled with water.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] They noticed that when the wires were brought together, each wire produced bubbles; one type produced hydrogen bubbles, and the other produced oxygen bubbles.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In 1785 a Dutch scientist named Martin van Marum created an electrostatic generator that he used to reduce tin, zinc and antimony from their salts using a process later known as electrolysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Though he unknowingly produced electrolysis, it was not until 1800 that William Nicholson and Anthony Carlisle discovered how electrolysis works.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In 1791, Luigi Galvani experimented with frog legs.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] He claimed that placing animal muscle between two dissimilar metal sheets resulted in electricity.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Responding to these claims, Alessandro Volta conducted his own tests.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] This would give insight to Humphry Davy's ideas on electrolysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] During preliminary experiments, Davy hypothesized that when two elements combine to form a compound, electrical energy is released.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Davy would go on to create Decomposition Tables from his preliminary experiments on Electrolysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The Decomposition Tables would give insight on the energies needed to break apart certain compounds.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In 1817, Johan August Arfwedson determined there was another element, lithium, in some of his samples; however, he could not isolate the component.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In 1821, William Thomas Brande used electrolysis to single it out, and two years later, he streamlined the process using lithium chloride and potassium chloride with electrolysis to produce lithium and lithium hydroxide.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] During the later years of Davy's research, Faraday became his assistant.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] While studying the process of electrolysis under Davy, Faraday discovered two laws of electrolysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] During the time of Maxwell and Faraday, concerns came about for electropositive and electronegative activities.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In November 1875, Paul Émile Lecoq de Boisbaudran discovered gallium using electrolysis of gallium hydroxide, producing 3.4 mg of gallium.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The following December, he presented his discovery of gallium to the *Académie des sciences* in Paris.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] On June 26, 1886, Ferdinand Frederick Henri Moissan finally felt comfortable performing electrolysis on anhydrous hydrogen fluoride to create a gaseous fluorine pure element.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Before he used hydrogen fluoride, Moissan used fluoride salts with electrolysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] On June 28, 1886, he performed his experiment in front of the *Académie des sciences* to show his discovery of the new element fluorine.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] While trying to find elemental fluorine through electrolysis of fluoride salts, many chemists perished, including Paulin Louyet and Jérôme Nicklès.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In 1886 Charles Martin Hall from America and Paul Héroult from France both filed for American patents for the electrolysis of aluminum, with Héroult submitting his in May, and Hall in July.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Hall was able to get his patent by proving through letters to his brother and family evidence that his method was discovered before the French patent was submitted.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] This became known as the Hall–Héroult process, which benefited many industries because aluminum's price then dropped from four dollars to thirty cents per pound.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In 1902 Polish engineer and inventor Stanisław Łaszczyński filed for and obtained Polish patent for the electrolysis of copper and zinc.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Electrolysis is the passing of a direct electric current through an electrolyte which is producing chemical reactions at the electrodes and decomposition of the materials.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The main components required to achieve electrolysis are an electrolyte, electrodes, and an external power source.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] A partition (e.g. an ion-exchange membrane or a salt bridge) is optional to keep the products from diffusing to the vicinity of the opposite electrode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The electrolyte is a chemical substance which contains free ions and carries electric current (e.g. an ion-conducting polymer, solution, or an ionic liquid compound).
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] If the ions are not mobile, as in most solid salts, then electrolysis cannot occur.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The electrodes are immersed separated by a distance such that a current flows between them through the electrolyte and are connected to the power source which completes the electrical circuit.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] A direct current supplied by the power source drives the reaction causing ions in the electrolyte to be attracted toward the respective oppositely charged electrode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Electrodes of metal, graphite and semiconductor material are widely used.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Choice of suitable electrode depends on chemical reactivity between the electrode and electrolyte and manufacturing cost.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Historically, when non-reactive anodes were desired for electrolysis, graphite (called plumbago in Faraday's time) or platinum were chosen.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] They were found to be some of the least reactive materials for anodes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Platinum erodes very slowly compared to other materials, and graphite crumbles and can produce carbon dioxide in aqueous solutions but otherwise does not participate in the reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Cathodes may be made of the same material, or they may be made from a more reactive material, since anode wear is greater due to oxidation at the anode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The key process of electrolysis is the interchange of atoms and ions by the removal or addition of electrons due to the applied potential.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The desired products of electrolysis are often in a different physical state from the electrolyte and can be removed by mechanical processes (e.g. by collecting gas above an electrode or precipitating a product out of the electrolyte).
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The quantity of the products is proportional to the current, and when two or more electrolytic cells are connected in series to the same power source, the products produced in the cells are proportional to their equivalent weight.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] These are known as Faraday's laws of electrolysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Each electrode attracts ions that are of the opposite charge.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Positively charged ions (cations) move towards the electron-providing (negative) cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Negatively charged ions (anions) move towards the electron-extracting (positive) anode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In this process, electrons are effectively introduced at the cathode as a reactant and removed at the anode as a product.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In chemistry, the loss of electrons is called oxidation, while electron gain is called reduction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] When neutral atoms or molecules, such as those on the surface of an electrode, gain or lose electrons they become ions and may dissolve in the electrolyte and react with other ions.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] When ions gain or lose electrons and become neutral, they will form compounds that separate from the electrolyte.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Positive metal ions like copper (ii) (Cu2+) deposit onto the cathode in a layer.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The terms for this are electroplating, electrowinning, and electrorefining.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] When an ion gains or loses electrons without becoming neutral, its electronic charge is altered in the process.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] For example, the electrolysis of brine produces hydrogen and chlorine gases which bubble from the electrolyte and are collected.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Without a partition between the electrodes, the OH− ions produced at the cathode are free to diffuse throughout the electrolyte to the anode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The more opportunity the Cl2 has to interact with NaOH in the solution, the less Cl2 emerges at the surface of the solution and the faster the production of hypochlorite progresses.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] This depends on factors such as solution temperature, the amount of time the Cl2 molecule is in contact with the solution, and concentration of NaOH.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Other reactions occur, such as the self-ionization of water and the decomposition of hypochlorite at the cathode, the rate of the latter depends on factors such as diffusion and the surface area of the cathode in contact with the electrolyte.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Decomposition potential or decomposition voltage refers to the minimum voltage (difference in electrode potential) between anode and cathode of an electrolytic cell that is needed for electrolysis to occur.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The voltage at which electrolysis is thermodynamically preferred is the difference of the electrode potentials as calculated using the Nernst equation.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Applying additional voltage, referred to as overpotential, can increase the rate of reaction and is often needed above the thermodynamic value.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] It is especially necessary for electrolysis reactions involving gases, such as oxygen, hydrogen or chlorine.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Oxidation of ions or neutral molecules occurs at the anode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Reduction of ions or neutral molecules occurs at the cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Neutral molecules can also react at either of the electrodes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In the last example, hydrogen ions (H+) also take part in the reaction and are provided by the acid in the solution, or by the solvent itself (water, methanol, etc.).
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Electrolysis reactions involving hydrogen ions are fairly common in acidic solutions.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In aqueous alkaline solutions, reactions involving hydroxide ions (OH−) are common.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Sometimes the solvents themselves (usually water) are oxidized or reduced at the electrodes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] It is even possible to have electrolysis involving gases, e.g. by using a gas diffusion electrode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The amount of electrical energy that must be added equals the change in Gibbs free energy of the reaction plus the losses in the system.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The losses can (in theory) be arbitrarily close to zero, so the maximum thermodynamic efficiency equals the enthalpy change divided by the free energy change of the reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In most cases, the electric input is larger than the enthalpy change of the reaction, so some energy is released in the form of heat.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In some cases, for instance, in the electrolysis of steam into hydrogen and oxygen at high temperature, the opposite is true and heat energy is absorbed.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] This heat is absorbed from the surroundings, and the heating value of the produced hydrogen is higher than the electric input.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Pulsating current results in products different from DC.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] For example, pulsing increases the ratio of ozone to oxygen produced at the anode in the electrolysis of an aqueous acidic solution such as dilute sulphuric acid.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Electrolysis of ethanol with pulsed current evolves an aldehyde instead of primarily an acid.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Galvanic cells and batteries use spontaneous, energy-releasing redox reactions to generate an electrical potential that provides useful power.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] When a secondary battery is charged, its redox reaction is run in reverse and the system can be considered as an electrolytic cell.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The chloralkali process is a large scale application of electrolysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] This technology supplies most of the chlorine and sodium hydroxide required by many industries.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The cathode is a mixed metal oxide clad titanium anode (also called a dimensionally stable anode).
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Many organofluorine compounds are produced by electrofluorination.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In the course of a typical synthesis, this reaction occurs once for each C–H bond in the precursor.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The cell potential is maintained near 5–6 V.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The anode, the electrocatalyst, is nickel-plated.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Acrylonitrile is converted to adiponitrile on an industrial scale via electrocatalysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Electroplating, where a thin film of metal is deposited over a substrate material.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Electroplating is used in many industries for either functional or decorative purposes, as in-vehicle bodies and nickel coins.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In Electrochemical machining, an electrolytic cathode is used as a shaped tool for removing material by anodic oxidation from a workpiece.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] ECM is often used as a technique for deburring or for etching metal surfaces like tools or knives with a permanent mark or logo.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Using a cell containing inert platinum electrodes, electrolysis of aqueous solutions of some salts leads to the reduction of the cations (such as metal deposition with, for example, zinc salts) and oxidation of the anions (such as the evolution of bromine with bromides).
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] However, with salts of some metals (such as sodium) hydrogen is evolved at the cathode, and for salts containing some anions (such as sulfate SO2− 4) oxygen is evolved at the anode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In both cases, this is due to water being reduced to form hydrogen or oxidized to form oxygen.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In principle, the voltage required to electrolyze a salt solution can be derived from the standard electrode potential for the reactions at the anode and cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The standard electrode potential is directly related to the Gibbs free energy, Δ*G*, for the reactions at each electrode and refers to an electrode with no current flowing.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] An extract from the table of standard electrode potentials is shown below.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Using the Nernst equation the electrode potential can be calculated for a specific concentration of ions, temperature and the number of electrons involved.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Comparable figures calculated in a similar way, for 1 M zinc bromide, ZnBr2, are −0.76 V for the reduction to Zn metal and +1.10 V for the oxidation producing bromine.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The conclusion from these figures is that hydrogen should be produced at the cathode and oxygen at the anode from the electrolysis of water—which is at variance with the experimental observation that zinc metal is deposited and bromine is produced.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The explanation is that these calculated potentials only indicate the thermodynamically preferred reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In practice, many other factors have to be taken into account such as the kinetics of some of the reaction steps involved.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] These factors together mean that a higher potential is required for the reduction and oxidation of water than predicted, and these are termed overpotentials.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Experimentally it is known that overpotentials depend on the design of the cell and the nature of the electrodes.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] For the electrolysis of a neutral (pH 7) sodium chloride solution, the reduction of sodium ion is thermodynamically very difficult and water is reduced evolving hydrogen leaving hydroxide ions in solution.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] At the anode the oxidation of chlorine is observed rather than the oxidation of water since the overpotential for the oxidation of chloride to chlorine is lower than the overpotential for the oxidation of water to oxygen.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The hydroxide ions and dissolved chlorine gas react further to form hypochlorous acid.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The aqueous solutions resulting from this process is called electrolyzed water and is used as a disinfectant and cleaning agent.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The electrolysis of carbon dioxide usually gives formate or carbon monoxide, but sometimes it produces more elaborate organic compounds such as ethylene.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] This finding has motivated intensive study.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Electrolysis of water produces hydrogen and oxygen in a ratio of 2 to 1 respectively.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The energy efficiency of water electrolysis varies widely.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The efficiency of an electrolyser is a measure of the enthalpy contained in the hydrogen (to undergo combustion with oxygen or some other later reaction), compared with the input electrical energy.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Heat/enthalpy values for hydrogen are well published in science and engineering texts, as 144 MJ/kg (40 kWh/kg).
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Note that fuel cells (not electrolysers) cannot use this full amount of heat/enthalpy, which has led to some confusion when calculating efficiency values for both types of technology.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] In the reaction, some energy is lost as heat.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Some reports quote efficiencies between 50% and 70% for alkaline electrolysers (50 kWh/kg); however, higher practical efficiencies are available with the use of polymer electrolyte membrane electrolysis and catalytic technology, such as 95% efficiency.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The National Renewable Energy Laboratory estimated in 2006 that 1 kg of hydrogen (roughly equivalent to 3 kg, or 4 liters, of petroleum in energy terms) could be produced by wind powered electrolysis for between US$5.55 in the near term and US$2.27 in the longer term.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] About 4% of hydrogen gas produced worldwide is generated by electrolysis, and normally used onsite.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Hydrogen is used for the creation of ammonia for fertilizer via the Haber process, and converting heavy petroleum sources to lighter fractions via hydrocracking.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Onsite electrolysis has been utilized to capture hydrogen for hydrogen fuel-cells in hydrogen vehicles.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] A specialized application of electrolysis involves the growth of conductive crystals on one of the electrodes from oxidized or reduced species that are generated in situ.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The technique has been used to obtain single crystals of low-dimensional electrical conductors, such as charge-transfer salts and linear chain compounds.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Iron for steel production, is produced by reduction of iron oxides using carbon.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The overall process is an example of carbothermal reduction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] One study of steel making in Germany found that producing 1 ton of steel emitted 2.1 tons of CO2e with 22% of that being direct emissions from the blast furnace.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] As of 2022, steel production contributes 7–9% of global emissions.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Electrolysis of iron would eliminate direct CO2 emissions.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The electrolysis of iron has been demonstrated in molten oxide salts using a platinum anode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] This method was performed a temperature of 1550 °C which presents a significant challenge to maintaining the reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Particularly, anode corrosion is a concern at these temperatures.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Additionally, the low temperature reduction of iron oxide in alkaline solutions has been reported.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The temperature is much lower than traditional iron production at 114 °C.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The low temperatures also tend to correlate with higher current efficiencies, with an efficiency of 95% being reported.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] While these methods are promising, they struggle to be cost competitive because of the large economies of scale keeping the price of blast furnace iron low.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] A 2020 study investigated direct electrolysis of seawater, alkaline electrolysis, proton-exchange membrane electrolysis, and solid oxide electrolysis.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Direct electrolysis of seawater follows known processes, forming an electrolysis cell in which the seawater acts as the electrolyte to allow for the reaction at the anode, 2 Cl−(aq) → Cl2(g) + 2e− and the reaction at the cathode, 2 H2O(l) + 2 e− → H2(g) + 2OH−(aq).
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The inclusion of magnesium and calcium ions in the seawater makes the production of alkali hydroxides possible that could form scales in the electrolyser cell, cutting down on lifespan and increasing the need for maintenance.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The electrolyte can easily get contaminated, but the alkaline electrolyser can operate under pressure to improve energy consumption.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The electrodes can be made of inexpensive materials and there's no requirement for an expensive catalyst in the design.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Many alternatives to this simple electrolyzer described exist.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Micro-electrolyzer designs are able to eliminate the separator requirement by designing the internal flow to separate the gases autonomously.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] See for example US 12116679B2 ("Device and method for large scale harvesting of solar energy through hydrogen production") where the operating pressure is increased to the point of Chlorine liquefaction so that sea water electrolyzer can proceed in a locally alkaline electrolytic fluid.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Removing separators allows operating at very high temperatures.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The structural design allows for operations at up to 700 bar thereby eliminating the need for hydrogen compressors.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] Solid oxide electrolysers run the reactions O−2(g) → 1/2 O2(g) + 2 e− at the anode and H2O(g) + 2 e− → H2(g) + O−2(g) at the cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] The solid oxide electrolysers require high temperatures (700–1,000 °C (1,292–1,832 °F)) to operate, generating superheated steam.
[src:electrochemistry/electrolysis] They suffer from degradation when turned off, making it a more inflexible hydrogen generation technology.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] A **galvanic cell** or **voltaic cell**, named after the scientists Luigi Galvani and Alessandro Volta, respectively, is an electrochemical cell in which an electric current is generated from spontaneous oxidation–reduction reactions.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] An example of a galvanic cell consists of two different metals, each immersed in separate beakers containing their respective metal ions in solution that are connected by a salt bridge or separated by a porous membrane.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Volta is the inventor of the voltaic pile, the first electrical battery.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Common usage of the word *battery* has evolved to include a single galvanic cell, but the first batteries had many galvanic cells.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] In 1780, Luigi Galvani discovered that when two different metals (e.g., copper and zinc) are in contact and then both are touched at the same time to two different parts of a muscle of a frog leg, to close the circuit, the frog's leg contracts.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The frog's leg, as well as being a detector of electrical current, was also the electrolyte (to use the language of modern chemistry).
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] A year after Galvani published his work (1790), Alessandro Volta showed that the frog was not necessary, using instead a force-based detector and brine-soaked paper (as electrolyte).
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Earlier Volta had established the law of capacitance *C* = ⁠*Q*/*V*⁠ with force-based detectors.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] In 1799 Volta invented the voltaic pile, which is a stack of galvanic cells each consisting of a metal disk, an electrolyte layer, and a disk of a different metal.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] He built it entirely out of non-biological material to challenge Galvani's (and the later experimenter Leopoldo Nobili)'s animal electricity theory in favor of his own metal-metal contact electricity theory.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Carlo Matteucci in his turn constructed a battery entirely out of biological material in answer to Volta.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Volta's contact electricity view characterized each electrode with a number that we would now call the work function of the electrode.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] This view ignored the chemical reactions at the electrode-electrolyte interfaces, which include H2 formation on the more noble metal in Volta's pile.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Although Volta did not understand the operation of the battery or the galvanic cell, these discoveries paved the way for electrical batteries; Volta's cell was named an IEEE Milestone in 1999.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Some forty years later, Faraday (see Faraday's laws of electrolysis) showed that the galvanic cell—now often called a voltaic cell—was chemical in nature.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Faraday introduced new terminology to the language of chemistry: electrode (cathode and anode), electrolyte, and ion (cation and anion).
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The authoritative work on the intellectual history of the voltaic cell remains that by Ostwald.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] It was suggested by Wilhelm König in 1940 that the object known as the Baghdad battery might represent galvanic cell technology from ancient Parthia.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Replicas filled with citric acid or grape juice have been shown to produce a voltage.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] However, it is far from certain that this was its purpose—other scholars have pointed out that it is very similar to vessels known to have been used for storing parchment scrolls.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Galvanic cells are extensions of spontaneous redox reactions, but have been merely designed to harness the energy produced from said reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] For example, when one immerses a strip of zinc metal (Zn) in an aqueous solution of copper sulfate (CuSO4), dark-colored solid deposits will collect on the surface of the zinc metal and the blue color characteristic of the Cu2+ ion disappears from the solution.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The depositions on the surface of the zinc metal consist of copper metal, and the solution now contains zinc ions.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] In this redox reaction, Zn is oxidized to Zn2+ and Cu2+ is reduced to Cu.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] When electrons are transferred directly from Zn to Cu2+, the enthalpy of reaction is lost to the surroundings as heat.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] However, the same reaction can be carried out in a galvanic cell, allowing some of the chemical energy released to be converted into electrical energy.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] In its simplest form, a half-cell consists of a solid metal (called an electrode) that is submerged in a solution; the solution contains cations (+) of the electrode metal and anions (−) to balance the charge of the cations.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The full cell consists of two half-cells, usually connected by a semi-permeable membrane or by a salt bridge that prevents the ions of the more noble metal from plating out at the other electrode.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] A specific example is the Daniell cell (see figure), with a zinc (Zn) half-cell containing a solution of ZnSO4 (zinc sulfate) and a copper (Cu) half-cell containing a solution of CuSO4 (copper sulfate).
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] A salt bridge is used here to complete the electric circuit.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] If an external electrical conductor connects the copper and zinc electrodes, zinc from the zinc electrode dissolves into the solution as Zn2+ ions (oxidation), releasing electrons that enter the external conductor.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] To compensate for the increased zinc ion concentration, via the salt bridge zinc ions (cations) leave and sulfate ions (anions) enter the zinc half-cell.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] In the copper half-cell, the copper ions plate onto the copper electrode (reduction), taking up electrons that leave the external conductor.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Since the Cu2+ ions (cations) plate onto the copper electrode, the latter is called the cathode.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Correspondingly the zinc electrode is the anode.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] This is the same reaction as given in the previous example.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] In addition, electrons flow through the external conductor, which is the primary application of the galvanic cell.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] As discussed under cell voltage, the electromotive force of the cell is the difference of the half-cell potentials, a measure of the relative ease of dissolution of the two electrodes into the electrolyte.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The emf depends on both the electrodes and on the electrolyte, an indication that the emf is chemical in nature.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] A half-cell contains a metal in two oxidation states.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] In other words, the metal atoms of one half-cell are oxidized while the metal cations of the other half-cell are reduced.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] By separating the metals in two half-cells, their reaction can be controlled in a way that forces transfer of electrons through the external circuit where they can do useful work.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The electrodes are connected with a metal wire in order to conduct the electrons that participate in the reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] This reduction reaction causes the free electrons throughout the metal B electrode, the wire, and the metal A electrode to be pulled into the metal B electrode.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Consequently, electrons are wrestled away from some of the atoms of the metal A electrode, as though the metal B cations were reacting directly with them; those metal A atoms become cations that dissolve into the surrounding solution.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The solutions of the half-cells are connected by a salt bridge or a porous plate that allows ions to pass from one solution to the other, which balances the charges of the solutions and allows the reaction to continue.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] By their nature, galvanic cells produce direct current.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The *Weston cell* has an anode composed of cadmium mercury amalgam, and a cathode composed of pure mercury.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The electrolyte is a (saturated) solution of cadmium sulfate.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The depolarizer is a paste of mercurous sulfate.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] When the electrolyte solution is saturated, the voltage of the cell is very reproducible; hence, in 1911, it was adopted as an international standard for voltage.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] In the strictest sense, a *battery* is a set of two or more galvanic cells that are connected in series to form a single source of voltage.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] For instance, a typical 12 V lead–acid battery has six galvanic cells connected in series, with the anodes composed of lead and cathodes composed of lead dioxide, both immersed in sulfuric acid.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Large central office battery rooms – in a telephone exchange to provide power for subscribers' land-line telephones, for instance – may have many cells, connected both in series and parallel: Individual cells are connected in series as a *battery* of cells with some standard voltage (c.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] 40 V), and *banks* of such serial batteries, themselves connected in parallel, to provide adequate amperage to supply a typical peak demand for telephone connections.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] where νe is the number of electrons transferred in the balanced half reactions, and F is Faraday's constant.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] However, it can be determined more conveniently by the use of a standard potential table for the two half cells involved.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The first step is to identify the two metals and their ions reacting in the cell.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Then one looks up the standard electrode potential, Eo, in volts, for each of the two half reactions.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The standard potential of the cell is equal to the more positive Eo value minus the more negative Eo value.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] For example, in the figure above the solutions are CuSO4 and ZnSO4.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Each solution has a corresponding metal strip in it, and a salt bridge or porous disk connecting the two solutions and allowing SO2−4 ions to flow freely between the copper and zinc solutions.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The standard potential for the reaction is then +0.34 V − (−0.76 V) = +1.10 V .
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The polarity of the cell is determined as follows.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Zinc metal is more strongly reducing than copper metal because the standard (reduction) potential for zinc is more negative than that of copper.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Thus, zinc metal will lose electrons to copper ions and develop a positive electrical charge.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Thus, at equilibrium, a few electrons are transferred, enough to cause the electrodes to be charged.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] where M n+ is the activity of the metal ion in solution.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] In practice concentration in ⁠ mol / L ⁠ is used in place of activity.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The metal electrode is in its standard state so by definition has unit activity.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The potential of the whole cell is obtained as the difference between the potentials for the two half-cells, so it depends on the concentrations of both dissolved metal ions.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] If the concentrations are the same the Nernst equation is not needed, and $~E_{\mathsf {cell}}~=~E_{\mathsf {cell}}^{\mathsf {\;\!o}}~~$ under the conditions assumed here.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The value of 2.303 ⁠ *R* / *F* ⁠ is 1.9845×10−4 ⁠ V / K ⁠ , so at *T* = 25 °C (298.15 K) the half-cell potential will change by only ⁠0.05918 V/ νe ⁠ if the concentration of a metal ion is increased or decreased by a factor of 10 .
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] These calculations are based on the assumption that all chemical reactions are in equilibrium.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] When a current flows in the circuit, equilibrium conditions are not achieved and the cell voltage will usually be reduced by various mechanisms, such as the development of overpotentials.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Also, since chemical reactions occur when the cell is producing power, the electrolyte concentrations change and the cell voltage is reduced.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] A consequence of the temperature dependency of standard potentials is that the voltage produced by a galvanic cell is also temperature dependent.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Galvanic corrosion is the electrochemical erosion of metals.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] Corrosion occurs when two dissimilar metals are in contact with each other in the presence of an electrolyte, such as salt water.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] This forms a galvanic cell, with hydrogen gas forming on the more noble (less active) metal.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] The resulting electrochemical potential then develops an electric current that electrolytically dissolves the less noble material.
[src:electrochemistry/galvanic-cell] A concentration cell can be formed if the same metal is exposed to two different concentrations of electrolyte.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] It was named after Walther Nernst, a German physical chemist who formulated the equation.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The reaction quotient (*Qr*), also often called the ion activity product (*IAP*), is the ratio between the chemical activities (*a*) of the reduced form (the reductant, aRed) and the oxidized form (the oxidant, aOx).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The chemical activity of a dissolved species corresponds to its true thermodynamic concentration taking into account the electrical interactions between all ions present in solution at elevated concentrations.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] For a given dissolved species, its chemical activity (a) is the product of its activity coefficient (γ) by its molar (mol/L solution), or molal (mol/kg water), concentration (C): a = γ C.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The standard thermodynamics also says that the actual Gibbs free energy Δ*G* is related to the free energy change under standard state Δ*G*o by the relationship: $\Delta G=\Delta G^{\ominus }+RT\ln Q_{r}$ where *Q*r is the reaction quotient and R is the universal ideal gas constant.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] At room temperature (25 °C), the thermal voltage $V_{T}={\frac {RT}{F}}$ is approximately 25.693 mV.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Similarly to equilibrium constants, activities are always measured with respect to the standard state (1 mol/L for solutes, 1 atm for gases, and T = 298.15 K, *i.e.*, 25 °C or 77 °F).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The chemical activity of a species i, *a*i, is related to the measured concentration *C*i via the relationship *a*i = *γ*i *C*i, where *γ*i is the activity coefficient of the species i.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] According to Wenzel (2020), a formal reduction potential $E_{\text{red}}^{\ominus '}$ is the reduction potential that applies to a half reaction under a set of specified conditions such as, e.g., pH, ionic strength, or the concentration of complexing agents.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The formal reduction potential $E_{\text{red}}^{\ominus '}$ is often a more convenient, but conditional, form of the standard reduction potential, taking into account activity coefficients and specific conditions characteristics of the reaction medium.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Therefore, its value is a conditional value, *i.e.*, that it depends on the experimental conditions and because the ionic strength affects the activity coefficients, $E_{\text{red}}^{\ominus '}$ will vary from medium to medium.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Several definitions of the formal reduction potential can be found in the literature, depending on the pursued objective and the experimental constraints imposed by the studied system.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The general definition of $E_{\text{red}}^{\ominus '}$ refers to its value determined when ${\frac {C_{\text{red}}}{C_{\text{ox}}}}=1$ .
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] A more particular case is when $E_{\text{red}}^{\ominus '}$ is also determined at pH 7, as e.g. for redox reactions important in biochemistry or biological systems.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The formal standard reduction potential $E_{\text{red}}^{\ominus '}$ can be defined as the measured reduction potential $E_{\text{red}}$ of the half-reaction at unity concentration ratio of the oxidized and reduced species (*i.e.*, when ⁠Cred/Cox⁠ = 1) under given conditions.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The formal reduction potential makes possible to more simply work with molar (mol/L, M) or molal (mol/kg H2O, m) concentrations in place of activities.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Because molar and molal concentrations were once referred as formal concentrations, it could explain the origin of the adjective *formal* in the expression *formal* potential.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The formal potential is thus the reversible potential of an electrode at equilibrium immersed in a solution where reactants and products are at unit concentration.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] If any small incremental change of potential causes a change in the direction of the reaction, *i.e.* from reduction to oxidation or *vice versa*, the system is close to equilibrium, reversible and is at its formal potential.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] When the formal potential is measured under standard conditions (*i.e.* the activity of each dissolved species is 1 mol/L, T = 298.15 K = 25 °C = 77 °F, Pgas = 1 bar) it becomes *de facto* a standard potential.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] In this case, as for the standard reduction potentials, the concentrations of dissolved species remain equal to one molar (M) or one molal (m), and so are said to be one formal (F).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The term formal concentration (F) is now largely ignored in the current literature and can be commonly assimilated to molar concentration (M), or molality (m) in case of thermodynamic calculations.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The formal potential is also found halfway between the two peaks in a cyclic voltammogram, where at this point the concentration of Ox (the oxidized species) and Red (the reduced species) at the electrode surface are equal.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Formal reduction potentials are applied to simplify calculations of a considered system under given conditions and measurements interpretation.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The experimental conditions in which they are determined and their relationship to the standard reduction potentials must be clearly described to avoid to confuse them with standard reduction potentials.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Formal standard reduction potentials ( $E_{\text{red}}^{\ominus '}$ ) are also commonly used in biochemistry and cell biology for referring to standard reduction potentials measured at pH 7, a value closer to the pH of most physiological and intracellular fluids than the standard state pH of 0.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The advantage is to defining a more appropriate redox scale better corresponding to real conditions than the standard state.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Formal standard reduction potentials ( $E_{\text{red}}^{\ominus '}$ ) allow to more easily estimate if a redox reaction supposed to occur in a metabolic process or to fuel microbial activity under some conditions is feasible or not.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] While, standard reduction potentials always refer to the standard hydrogen electrode (SHE), with [ H+] = 1 M corresponding to a pH 0, and $E_{\text{red H+}}^{\ominus }$ fixed arbitrarily to zero by convention, it is no longer the case at a pH of 7.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Then, the reduction potential $E_{\text{red}}$ of a hydrogen electrode operating at pH 7 is −0.413 V with respect to the standard hydrogen electrode (SHE).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The $E_{h}$ and pH of a solution are related by the Nernst equation as commonly represented by a Pourbaix diagram ( $E_{h}$ – pH plot). $E_{h}$ explicitly denotes $E_{\text{red}}$ expressed versus the standard hydrogen electrode (SHE).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] where $\Delta G^{\ominus }$ is the standard Gibbs free energy change, z is the number of electrons involved, and F is the Faraday's constant.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] where curly brackets indicate activities, and exponents are shown in the conventional manner.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] This equation is the equation of a straight line for $E_{\text{red}}$ as a function of pH with a slope of $-0.05916\,\left({\frac {h}{z}}\right)$ volt (pH has no units).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] This equation predicts lower $E_{\text{red}}$ at higher pH values.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The main factor affecting the formal reduction potentials in biochemical or biological processes is most often the pH.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] To determine approximate values of formal reduction potentials, neglecting in a first approach changes in activity coefficients due to ionic strength, the Nernst equation has to be applied taking care to first express the relationship as a function of pH.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The second factor to be considered are the values of the concentrations taken into account in the Nernst equation.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] To define a formal reduction potential for a biochemical reaction, the pH value, the concentrations values and the hypotheses made on the activity coefficients must always be explicitly indicated.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] When using, or comparing, several formal reduction potentials they must also be internally consistent.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Problems may occur when mixing different sources of data using different conventions or approximations (*i.e.*, with different underlying hypotheses).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] To illustrate the dependency of the reduction potential on pH, one can simply consider the two oxido-reduction equilibria determining the water stability domain in a Pourbaix diagram (Eh–pH plot).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] When water is submitted to electrolysis by applying a sufficient difference of electrical potential between two electrodes immersed in water, hydrogen is produced at the cathode (reduction of water protons) while oxygen is formed at the anode (oxidation of water oxygen atoms).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The same may occur if a reductant stronger than hydrogen (e.g., metallic Na) or an oxidant stronger than oxygen (e.g., F2) enters in contact with water and reacts with it.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Note that the slopes of the two water stability domain upper and lower lines are the same (−59.16 mV/pH unit), so they are parallel on a Pourbaix diagram.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] As the slopes are negative, at high pH, both hydrogen and oxygen evolution requires a much lower reduction potential than at low pH.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] = −0.414 V for the reduction of protons.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The offset of −414 mV in $E_{\text{red}}$ is the same for both reduction reactions because they share the same linear relationship as a function of pH and the slopes of their lines are the same.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] This can be directly verified on a Pourbaix diagram.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The determination of the formal reduction potential at pH = 7 for a given biochemical half-reaction requires thus to calculate it with the corresponding Nernst equation as a function of pH.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] One cannot simply apply an offset of −414 mV to the Eh value (SHE) when the ratio *h⁄z* differs from 1.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Beside important redox reactions in biochemistry and microbiology, the Nernst equation is also used in physiology for calculating the electric potential of a cell membrane with respect to one type of ion.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] It can be linked to the acid dissociation constant.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The Nernst equation has a physiological application when used to calculate the potential of an ion of charge *z* across a membrane.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] When the membrane is in thermodynamic equilibrium (i.e., no net flux of ions), and if the cell is permeable to only one ion, then the membrane potential must be equal to the Nernst potential for that ion.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The potential across the cell membrane that exactly opposes net diffusion of a particular ion through the membrane is called the Nernst potential for that ion.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] As seen above, the magnitude of the Nernst potential is determined by the ratio of the concentrations of that specific ion on the two sides of the membrane.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The greater this ratio the greater the tendency for the ion to diffuse in one direction, and therefore the greater the Nernst potential required to prevent the diffusion.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] A similar expression exists that includes r (the absolute value of the transport ratio).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] This takes transporters with unequal exchanges into account.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] See: sodium-potassium pump where the transport ratio would be 2/3, so r equals 1.5 in the formula below.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The reason why we insert a factor r = 1.5 here is that current density *by electrochemical force* Je.c.(Na+) + Je.c.(K+) is no longer zero, but rather Je.c.(Na+) + 1.5Je.c.(K+) = 0 (as for both ions flux by electrochemical force is compensated by that by the pump, i.e.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Je.c. = −Jpump), altering the constraints for applying GHK equation.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The other variables are the same as above.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The following example includes two ions: potassium (K+) and sodium (Na+).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] and that have a standard potential of zero, and in which the activities are well represented by the concentrations (i.e. unit activity coefficient).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The chemical potential *μ*c of this solution is the difference between the energy barriers for taking electrons from and for giving electrons to the working electrode that is setting the solution's electrochemical potential.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Quantities here are given per molecule, not per mole, and so Boltzmann constant *k* and the electron charge *e* are used instead of the gas constant *R* and Faraday's constant *F*.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] To convert to the molar quantities given in most chemistry textbooks, it is simply necessary to multiply by the Avogadro constant: *R* = *kN*A and *F* = *eN*A.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] where Ω is the number of states available to the molecule.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The number of states must vary linearly with the volume *V* of the system (here an idealized system is considered for better understanding, so that activities are posited very close to the true concentrations).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Fundamental statistical proof of the mentioned linearity goes beyond the scope of this section, but to see this is true it is simpler to consider usual isothermal process for an ideal gas where the change of entropy Δ*S* = *nR* ln(⁠*V*2/*V*1⁠) takes place.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] It follows from the definition of entropy and from the condition of constant temperature and quantity of gas n that the change in the number of states must be proportional to the relative change in volume ⁠*V*2/*V*1⁠.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] If state 1 is at standard conditions, in which *c*1 is unity (e.g., 1 atm or 1 M), it will merely cancel the units of *c*2.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] We can, therefore, write the entropy of an arbitrary molecule A as $S(\mathrm {A} )=S^{\ominus }(\mathrm {A} )-k\ln[\mathrm {A} ],$ where $S^{\ominus }$ is the entropy at standard conditions and [A] denotes the concentration of A.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Under certain circumstances (see chemical equilibrium), each activity term, such as *aνj j* may be replaced by a concentration term, [A].In an electrochemical cell, the cell potential *E* is the chemical potential available from redox reactions (*E* = ⁠*μ*c/*e*⁠).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] *E* is related to the Gibbs free energy change Δ*G* only by a constant: Δ*G* = −*zFE*, where *z* is the number of electrons transferred and *F* is the Faraday constant.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] There is a negative sign because a spontaneous reaction has a negative Gibbs free energy Δ*G* and a positive potential *E*.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The Gibbs free energy is related to the entropy by *G* = *H* − *TS*, where *H* is the enthalpy and *T* is the temperature of the system.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] This is the more general form of the Nernst equation.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The sign is negative, because the considered system performs the work and thus releases energy.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Starting from the Nernst equation, one can also demonstrate the same relationship in the reverse way.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] We have thus related the standard electrode potential and the equilibrium constant of a redox reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] In dilute solutions, the Nernst equation can be expressed directly in the terms of concentrations (since activity coefficients are close to unity).
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] But at higher concentrations, the true activities of the ions must be used.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] This complicates the use of the Nernst equation, since estimation of non-ideal activities of ions generally requires experimental measurements.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The Nernst equation also only applies when there is no net current flow through the electrode.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The activity of ions at the electrode surface changes when there is current flow, and there are additional overpotential and resistive loss terms which contribute to the measured potential.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] At very low concentrations of the potential-determining ions, the potential predicted by Nernst equation approaches toward ±∞.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] This is physically meaningless because, under such conditions, the exchange current density becomes very low, and there may be no thermodynamic equilibrium necessary for Nernst equation to hold.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The electrode is called unpoised in such case.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Other effects tend to take control of the electrochemical behavior of the system, like the involvement of the solvated electron in electricity transfer and electrode equilibria, as analyzed by Alexander Frumkin and B.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The expression of time dependence has been established by Karaoglanoff.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The Nernst equation has been involved in the scientific controversy about cold fusion.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Fleischmann and Pons, claiming that cold fusion could exist, calculated that a palladium cathode immersed in a heavy water electrolysis cell could achieve up to 1027 atmospheres of pressure inside the crystal lattice of the metal of the cathode, enough pressure to cause spontaneous nuclear fusion.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] In reality, only 10,000–20,000 atmospheres were achieved.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] Huizenga claimed their original calculation was affected by a misinterpretation of the Nernst equation.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] The Nernst equation allows the calculation of the extent of reaction between two redox systems and can be used, for example, to assess whether a particular reaction will go to completion or not.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] At chemical equilibrium, the electromotive forces (emf) of the two half cells are equal.
[src:electrochemistry/nernst-equation] This allows the equilibrium constant *K* of the reaction to be calculated and hence the extent of the reaction.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] The basis for an electrochemical cell, such as the galvanic cell, is always a redox reaction which can be broken down into two half-reactions: oxidation at anode (loss of electron) and reduction at cathode (gain of electron).
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] Electricity is produced due to the difference of electric potential between the individual potentials of the two metal electrodes with respect to the electrolyte.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] Although the overall potential of a cell can be measured, there is no simple way to accurately measure the electrode/electrolyte potentials in isolation.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] The electric potential also varies with temperature, concentration and pressure.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] Since the oxidation potential of a half-reaction is the negative of the reduction potential in a redox reaction, it is sufficient to calculate either one of the potentials.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] Therefore, standard electrode potential is commonly written as standard reduction potential.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] The galvanic cell potential results from the voltage difference of a *pair* of electrodes.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] It is not possible to measure an absolute value for each electrode separately.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] However, the potential of a reference electrode, standard hydrogen electrode (SHE), is defined as to 0.00 V.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] An electrode with unknown electrode potential can be paired with either the standard hydrogen electrode, or another electrode whose potential has already been measured, to determine its "absolute" potential.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] Since the electrode potentials are conventionally defined as reduction potentials, the sign of the potential for the metal electrode being oxidized must be reversed when calculating the overall cell potential.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] For practical measurements, the electrode in question is connected to the positive terminal of the electrometer, while the standard hydrogen electrode is connected to the negative terminal.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] A reversible electrode is an electrode that owes its potential to changes of a reversible nature.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] A first condition to be fulfilled is that the system is close to the chemical equilibrium.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] A second set of conditions is that the system is submitted to very small solicitations spread on a sufficient period of time so, that the chemical equilibrium conditions nearly always prevail.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] In theory, it is very difficult to experimentally achieve reversible conditions because any perturbation imposed to a system near equilibrium in a finite time forces it out of equilibrium.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] However, if the solicitations exerted on the system are sufficiently small and applied slowly, one can consider an electrode to be reversible.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] By nature, electrode reversibility depends on the experimental conditions and the way the electrode is operated.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] For example, electrodes used in electroplating are operated with a high over-potential to force the reduction of a given metal cation to be deposited onto a metallic surface to be protected.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] The larger the value of the standard reduction potential, the easier it is for the element to be reduced (gain electrons); in other words, they are better oxidizing agents.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] The highly positive standard reduction potential of F2 means it is reduced easily and is therefore a good oxidizing agent.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] In contrast, the greatly negative standard reduction potential of Li+ indicates that it is not easily reduced.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] Instead, Li(*s*) would rather undergo oxidation (hence it is a good reducing agent).
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] Zn2+ has a standard reduction potential of −0.76 V and thus can be oxidized by any other electrode whose standard reduction potential is greater than −0.76 V (e.g., H+ (0 V), Cu2+ (0.34 V), F2 (2.87 V)) and can be reduced by any electrode with standard reduction potential less than −0.76 V (e.g.
[src:electrochemistry/standard-electrode-potential] where n is number of moles of electrons per mole of products and F is the Faraday constant, ~ 96 485 C/mol.
